sec.p:
Hypericum perforatum
L. (family: Hypericaceae ), or else St John's wort, is a plant species with many traditional uses worldwide. It is also the source of top–selling herbal medicinal products mainly for mild–- to–moderate depression, a use which is supported by many clinical studies (
,
). The hydroalcoholic extracts of
H. perforatum
aerial parts are rich in phenolic acid derivatives, xanthones, flavonoids (especially quercetin glycosides), proanthocyanidins, naphthodianthrones and phloroglucinols. An array of biological actions has been attributed to its metabolites, but it has been difficult to ascribe the biological and therapeutic effects of the extract to only one ingredient, and thus the extract is considered as the active principle (
).
H. perforatum
remains the most illustrative example of the potential herb–drug interactions, side–effects and the need for educated phytomedicine use and quality control. In this context, safe daily dose of hyperforin, the main phloroglucinol, has been set at < 1 mg (Chrubasik Hausmann et al., 2019), while hypericin, a naphthodianthrone that can be used in photodynamic therapy and in diagnosis, causes photosensitization as a side effect (
). Interesting biological properties, mainly antimicrobial (
), have been ascribed to
Hypericum
essential oils, although the genus is generally poor in essential oils (oil yield <1%, w/ w).

About 500 

Hypericum
species

have been identified all over the world (

), whilst the Mediterranean basin is considered as one of the biodiversity hotspots for 

Hypericum
(
Nurk and Crockett, 2011
)

. Many of those taxa are used in traditional medicine interchangeably with 

H. perforatum

and some are used in the St John's wort final products (

; 

; 

), but only the latter is listed in the Pharmacopoeias and in the monographs of both the European Medicines Agency and the World Health Organization. The secondary metabolites of different species vary, but, even within the same species, both the extract's and the essential oil's composition is not stable since it depends on different factors such as genotype, environmental conditions, post–harvest treatment and extraction conditions; all of them resulting to variation of its therapeutic efficacy (

).

A
comprehensive metabolomic analysis enables the screening of hundreds of metabolites in an untargeted manner, contributing thus significantly to the authentication of the final products and the identification of novel polar metabolites (

; 

; 

; 

). Only a few studies of 

Hypericum

taxa have assumed a metabolomic approach or even the monitoring of the most abundant and medicinally important metabolites (

; 

; 

), whereas limited studies have combined GC–MS and LC–MS analysis in parallel (

; 

). Furthermore, metabolomic analysis attributes chemotaxonomic value (

; 

; 

).

Characterization of plant germplasm using molecular techniques plays an increasingly important role in the management and identification of plant genetic resources, since DNA is not affected by the environment and the developmental stage of the plant, as morphological characters usually do (

). The nuclear ribosomal internal transcribed spacer (nrITS) region or a part of it (ITS2) is one of the most frequently used nuclear markers for the identification and the phylogenetic reconstructions at the species level or even below (Li et al., 2011; 

). So far, the nrITS region has been used for inferring phylogenies (

; 

) and for species authentication in the genus 

Hypericum

(

; 

).

Hypericum
essential oils are complex chemical mixtures of a wide variety of volatiles (
;
); they include aliphatic hydrocarbons, the monoterpenes α – and β –pinene, and the sesquiterpenes (
E
)– β –caryophyllene and caryophyllene oxide. Although there are several studies regarding the essential oils’ composition of
H. perforatum ssp. veronense
(former:
H. perforatum ssp. angustifolium
),
H. perfoliatum
,
H. triquetrifolium
and
H. empetrifolium
(
;
;
;
;
,
,
;
), this is the first investigation, to our knowledge, of the essential oil composition of
H. empetrifolium ssp. empetrifolium
.

